    <item>
      <title>Bit Flipping</title>
      <link>https://dangpham112000.github.io/docs/research/security/bit_flipping/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 16 Jan 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://dangpham112000.github.io/docs/research/security/bit_flipping/</guid>
      <description>&lt;h1 id=&#34;bit-flipping-attack&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Bit Flipping Attack&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#bit-flipping-attack&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h1&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;As you can see in the &lt;a href=&#34;https://dangpham112000.github.io/docs/research/security/packet_sniffing/&#34;&gt;Packet Sniffing&lt;/a&gt; section, we have a discussion about how messages that go through the internet can easily be seen by hackers. One of our protection solutions is to &lt;strong&gt;encrypt all packets that go through the internet&lt;/strong&gt;, but &lt;strong&gt;is it enough?&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;use-case&#34;&gt;&#xA;  Use case&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#use-case&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;Attacking financial systems&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;h2 id=&#34;how-it-works&#34;&gt;&#xA;  How it works&#xA;  &lt;a class=&#34;anchor&#34; href=&#34;#how-it-works&#34;&gt;#&lt;/a&gt;&#xA;&lt;/h2&gt;&#xA;&lt;ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;An attacker alters bits in the ciphertext to produce a predictable change in the plaintext&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;By flipping specific bits, the attacker can control certain parts of the plaintext, potentially altering critical information&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;li&gt;This manipulation allows the attacker to modify the encrypted message without needing to decrypt it first&lt;/li&gt;&#xA;&lt;/ul&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;img src=&#34;https://dangpham112000.github.io/research/security/bit_flipping/bit_flipping.png&#34; alt=&#34;bit_flipping&#34; /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</description>
    </item>
